    <subsection xml:id="subsec-Illustrating_simple_linear_inequality_on_a_number_line">
      <title>Illustrating simple linear inequality on a number line</title>

      <p>
        <term>Number Line.</term>
      </p>

      <p>
        A <em><term>number line</term></em> is a straight horizontal line used to represent numbers. It helps us visualize numbers, compare values, and understand inequalities easily.
      </p>

      <p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              A number line extends infinitely in both directions.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              It has a zero <m>(0)</m> in the center, with positive numbers to the right and negative numbers to the left.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The numbers increase as we move to the right and decrease as we move to the left.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The numbers are evenly spaced on the line.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>

      <p>
        Take a look at the numberline below:
      </p>

      <image>
        <shortdescription>Number Line Illustrastion.</shortdescription>
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Draw number line starting at 0
            \draw[&lt;-&gt;](0,0) -- (8.5,0);

            % Draw ticks and labels for numbers from 0 to 8
            \foreach \x in {0,1,...,8} {
                \draw (\x,0.1) -- (\x,-0.1);
                \node[below] at (\x,-0.1) {\x}; 
            }

            % Draw curved arrows for jumps
            \draw[red,-&gt;] (5,0.1) to[bend right=60] (4,0.1);
            \draw[red,-&gt;] (4,0.2) to[bend right=60] (3,0.1);
            \draw[red,-&gt;] (3,0.2) to[bend right=60] (2,0.1);

            % Start label
            \draw[] (5,0) -- (5,0.5);
            \node[above] at (5,0.55) {\textbf{start}};

            % Stop label
            \draw[] (2,0) -- (2,0.5);
            \node[above] at (2,0.55) {\textbf{stop}};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>

      <activity>

        <p>
          <term>Work in Groups.</term>
        </p>

        <p>

          <ol>

            <li>
              
              <p>
                Consider <em>x &gt; 2.</em>
              </p>
                
            </li>

            <li>
              
              <p>
                Draw a number line.
              </p>

            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Identify some of the numbers that satisfy the inequality.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>

              <p>
                Confirm whether the numbers are to the left or right of digit 2.
              </p>
            
            </li>

            <li>
              
              <p>
                Circle digit 2.
              </p>

            </li>

            <li>

              <p>
                From the circle, draw an arrow facing the direction with numbers which satisfy the inequality.
              </p>
            
            </li>

            <li>
              
              <p>
                Discuss and share with others.
              </p>
            
            </li>

          </ol>

        </p>
        
      </activity>

      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow> \amp {\color{blue} \text{Learning Points.}} </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        
        <ol>

          <li>

            <p>
              <m>{\color{green} \text{For inequalities with symbols} (\lt) \text{or} (\gt), \text{the boundary digits are circled in the representations.}}</m>
            </p>

          </li>

          <li>

            <p>
              <m>{\color{green} \text{For inequalities with symbols (\le) \text{or} (\ge), the circles are shaded.}}</m>
            </p>

          </li>

        </ol>

      </p>

      <p>
        <m>{\color{green} \text{We can illustrate inequalities on a number line by understanding the inequality symbols.}}</m>
      </p>

      <p>
        <m>{\color{green} \text{An "open point" is used to represent a number that is not included in the inequality.}}</m>
      </p>

      <p>
        <m>{\color{green} \text{Take a look at the illustration below;}}</m>
      </p>

      <p>
        <m>{\color{green} \text{Illustrate on a number line.} (x &gt; 6)}</m>
      </p>

      <image>
        <shortdescription>Open point numberline</shortdescription>
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Draw number line
            \draw[thick, ->] (4,0) -- (10,0);
            
            % Draw open circle above x=6 with an arrow
            \draw (6,0.5) circle (3pt);
            \draw[thick, ->] (6.2,0.5) -- (9,0.5);
            
            % Draw arrow to the right on the number line
            \draw[thick] (6.1,0) -- (10,0);
            
            % Label points
            \node[below] at (6,0) {6};
            \foreach \x in {5,7,8,9} {
                \node[below] at (\x,0) {\x};
            }
            
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
        
      </image>

      <p>
        <m>{\color{green} \text{An "open point" has been used since} 6 \text{in not part of the solution of the inequality.}}</m>
      </p>

      <p>
        <m>{\color{green} \text{A "closed point" is used to represent a number that is included in the inequality.}}</m>
      </p>

      <p>
        <m>{\color{green} \text{Take a look at the illustration below;}}</m>
      </p>

      <p>
        <me>{\color{green} (x \ge 4)}</me>        
      </p>

      <image>
        <shortdescription>closed point inequality</shortdescription>
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Draw number line
            \draw[thick, ->] (1,0) -- (10,0);
            
            % Draw closed circle above x=6 with an arrow
            \filldraw (4,0.5) circle (3pt);
            \draw[thick, ->] (4.2,0.5) -- (9,0.5);
            
            % Draw arrow to the right on the number line
            \draw[thick] (4.1,0) -- (10,0);
            
            % Label points
            \node[below] at (4,0) {4};
            \foreach \x in {1,2,3,5,6,7,8,9} {
                \node[below] at (\x,0) {\x};
            }
            
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
        
      </image>

      <p>
        <m>{\color{green} \text{A closed point has been used since} (4) \text{is part of the solution of the inequality.}}</m>
      </p>

      <example>

          <statement>

            <p>
              Illustrate <m>x &gt; 2</m> on a number line.
            </p>

          </statement>

          <solution>
            
            <p>
              Circle at digit <m>2</m> and draw a line pointing towards numbers greater than <m>2</m>.
            </p>

            <image>
              <shortdescription>Open point numberline</shortdescription>
              <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                  % Draw number line
                  \draw[thick, ->] (-1,0) -- (10,0);
                  
                  % Draw open circle above x=2 with an arrow
                  \draw (2,0.5) circle (3pt);
                  \draw[thick, ->] (2.2,0.5) -- (9,0.5);
                  
                  % Draw arrow to the right on the number line
                  \draw[thick] (2.1,0) -- (10,0);
                  
                  % Label points
                  \node[below] at (2,0) {2};
                  \foreach \x in {1,3,4,5,6,7,8,9} {
                      \node[below] at (\x,0) {\x};
                  }
                  
                \end{tikzpicture}
              </latex-image>
              
            </image>

          </solution>

      </example>

      <example>

        <statement>

            <p>
              Illustrate <m>x \ge 8</m> on a number line
            </p>

        </statement>
            
        <solution>

          <p>
              Draw a circle at digit <m>8</m> and shade it then draw a line towards digits greater than <m>8</m>.
          </p>

          <image>
            <shortdescription>closed point inequality</shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                % Draw number line
                \draw[thick, ->] (5,0) -- (15,0);
                
                % Draw closed circle above x=6 with an arrow
                \filldraw (8,0.5) circle (3pt);
                \draw[thick, ->] (8.2,0.5) -- (14,0.5);
                
                % Draw arrow to the right on the number line
                \draw[thick] (8.1,0) -- (15,0);
                
                % Label points
                \node[below] at (8,0) {8};
                \foreach \x in {5,6,7,9,10,11,12,13,14} {
                    \node[below] at (\x,0) {\x};
                }
                
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            
          </image>

        </solution>

      </example>

